Using the solution from part d. and plugging in $\displaystyle M = K/4$,
we have

\begin{align*}
\frac{K}{4} = M &= \frac{K \mp K\sqrt{1-\tfrac{2H}{K}}}{2} \\
\end{align*}

Multiplying by 2 and noticing that the original differential equation
has the restriction that \emph{K} cannot be 0, we may divide by K as
well to reduce the problem to

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{2} = M &= 1 \mp \sqrt{1-\tfrac{2H}{K}}\\
\end{align*}

Isolating for the square root and squaring both sides gives

\begin{align*}
\frac{1}{4} = M &= 1-\tfrac{2H}{K}\\
\end{align*}

Solving for \emph{H} gives

$\displaystyle H = \frac{3}{8}K$
